O = (0,0);
A = dir(90);
B = dir(-30);
C = dir(210);
D = extension(B, B + rotate(90)*(B), C, C + rotate(90)*(C));
E = dir(150);
F = (B + C)/2;

draw(Circle(O,1));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(B--D--C);
draw(A--E);
draw(A--F);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SE);
label("$C$", C, SW);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$E$", E, NW);
label("$F$", F, S);
[/asy]

By symmetry, $AF$ is also the perpendicular bisector of $BC,$ so $BF = FC$ and $BE = EC.$  Since $\angle BAC = k \pi,$ $\angle BOC = 2 \angle BAC = 2k \pi,$ where $O$ is the center of the circle.  Then $\angle BOC = 2 \angle BEC,$ so $k = \boxed{\frac{3}{2}}.$

Let $E$ and $F$ be the points where the circle is tangent to lines $AB$ and $AC,$ respectively.

[asy]
import graph;

unitsize(2 cm);

pair O, A, B, C, D, E, F;

O = (0,0);
A = dir(90);
B = dir(-30);
C = dir(210);
D = extension(B, B + rotate(90)*(B), C, C + rotate(90)*(C));
E = tangent(B, O, 1, 2);
F = tangent(C, O, 1, 2);

draw(Circle(O,1));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(B--D--C);
draw(O--E);
draw(O--F);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SE);
label("$C$", C, SW);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$E$", E, NE);
label("$F$", F, NW);
[/asy]

Since $AB = AC,$ we have $\angle BAE = \angle CAF.$  Also, $\angle ABE = \angle ACF = 90^\circ,$ so $\triangle ABE \sim \triangle ACF.$  Therefore, $AE^2 = AB \cdot AC.$  Similarly, $AF^2 = AB \cdot AC.$  Hence, $AE = AF,$ so $AD$ is an angle bisector of $\angle BAC.$

Also, $\angle ADB = \angle ACB = 2 \angle D,$ so $\angle ABD = \angle ACD = 90^\circ - \angle D.$  Then $\angle BAD = \angle DAC = \angle D,$ so $\triangle ABD$ and $\triangle ACD$ are isosceles.  Hence, $AB = AD$ and $AC = AD,$ so $AB = AC.$  Then $\angle BAC = \pi - 2 \angle D,$ so $k = \boxed{1 - 2 \angle D/\pi}.$

Let $E$ be the midpoint of arc $BC.$  Then $AE$ is the angle bisector of $\angle BAC,$ so $AE$ passes through the incenter $I$ of triangle $ABC.$

[asy]
import graph;

unitsize(2 cm);

pair O, A, B, C, D, E, I;

O = (0,0);
A = dir(90);
B = dir(-30);
C = dir(210);
D = extension(B, B + rotate(90)*(B), C, C + rotate(90)*(C));
E = dir(120);
I = incenter(A,B,C);

draw(Circle(O,1));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(B--D--C);
draw(A--E);
draw(I--E);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SE);
label("$C$", C, SW);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$E$", E, NW);
label("$I$", I, S);
[/asy]

Since $\angle BAC = k \pi,$ we have $\angle BEC = 2 \pi - k \pi = (2 - k) \pi.$  Since $EB = EC,$ $\angle EBI = \frac{(2 - k) \pi}{2} = (1 - k) \pi.$  Then $\angle ABI = \frac{\pi}{2} - \frac{(1 - k) \pi}{2} = \frac{(k + 1) \pi}{4}.$

Since $ABC$ is isosceles, $\angle BAC = \angle BCA,$ so $\angle ABI = \angle CBI.$  Therefore, $\angle IBC = \frac{(1 - k) \pi}{4}.$

Since $BD$ and $CD$ are tangent to the circle, $\angle DBC = \angle DCB,$ so
\[\angle BDC = \pi - \angle DBC - \angle DCB = \frac{\pi}{2} - \frac{(1 - k) \pi}{4} = \frac{(3 + k) \pi}{8}.\]But $\angle BDC = 2 \angle D,$ so $2 \angle D = \frac{(3 + k) \pi}{8}.$  Then $\angle BAC = 2 \angle D,$ so
\[k \pi = 16 \angle D = \frac{8}{3 + k} \cdot 2 \angle D = \frac{4}{3 + k} \cdot \frac{(3 + k) \pi}{4}.\]Therefore, $k = \boxed{4}.$

Let $O$ be the center of the circle.  Then $\angle BOC = 2 \angle D,$ so $\angle BAC = \pi - 2 \angle D = \frac{\pi}{2} - \angle BOC.$

[asy]
