Then $OD = OE = OF = R = 20.$  By the Pythagorean theorem,
\begin{align*}
AH^2 &= AD^2 - DH^2 = 15^2 - \left( \frac{2 \cdot [ABC]}{BC} \right)^2 = \frac{392}{3}, \\
BH^2 &= BE^2 - EH^2 = 13^2 - \left( \frac{2 \cdot [ABC]}{CA} \right)^2 = \frac{140}{3}, \\
CH^2 &= CF^2 - FH^2 = 14^2 - \left( \frac{2 \cdot [ABC]}{AB} \right)^2 = \frac{476}{3}.
\end{align*}By the Law of Cosines on triangles $AHB$, $BHC$, and $CHA$, respectively,
\begin{align*}
\cos A &= \frac{AH^2 + BH^2 - AB^2}{2 \cdot AH \cdot BH} = -\frac{33}{65}, \\
\cos B &= \frac{BH^2 + CH^2 - BC^2}{2 \cdot BH \cdot CH} = -\frac{48}{65}, \\
\cos C &= \frac{CH^2 + AH^2 - CA^2}{2 \cdot CH \cdot AH} = -\frac{7}{65}.
\end{align*}Then by the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC$,
\begin{align*}
\cos A &= \frac{BC^2 + CA^2 - AB^2}{2 \cdot BC \cdot CA} \\
&= \frac{(14^2 + 15^2 - 13^2)/2}{14 \cdot 15} \\
&= \frac{53}{70}.
\end{align*}We have that $\cos A = -\cos B \cos C,$ so
\[\frac{33}{65} = \frac{48}{65} \cdot \frac{7}{65}.\]Hence, $\frac{m \sqrt{n}}{k} = OH = R \cos A = 20 \cdot \frac{53}{70} = \frac{106}{7},$ and $m + n + k = \boxed{123}.$

Let $\Gamma$ be the sphere.  Let $P$ be the orthogonal projection of $O$ onto plane $ABC$, and let $R$ be the circumradius of $\triangle ABC$.  Then $P$ is the circumcenter of $\triangle ABC$, so $OR = RP = R$.  Let $D$, $E$, and $F$ be the midpoints of $\overline{BC}$, $\overline{CA}$, and $\overline{AB}$, respectively.  Then $OD = OE = OF = OP = R$, so $O$ lies on the sphere with center $P$ and radius $R$.

[asy]
import three;

size(220);
currentprojection = perspective(6,3,2);

triple A, B, C, D, E, F, O, P;

A = (0,0,20);
B = (0.97,0.24,-19.6);
C = (2.4,-13.25,8.2);
O = (0,-5,12);
P = (0,-5,20);
D = (B + C)/2;
E = (C + A)/2;
F = (A + B)/2;

draw(surface(unitball), white, nolight);
draw(O--P);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(P--B);
draw(P--C);
draw(P--A);
draw(D--E--F--cycle);
draw(O--B,dashed);
draw(O--C,dashed);
draw(O--A,dashed);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, E);
label("$C$", C, SW);
label("$D$", D, SE);
